<div class="prose max-w-none">

  <p>The Chinese zodiac (生肖 shēngxiào) is a 12-year cycle where each year is represented by an animal. Unlike Western astrology, which is based on birth month, the Chinese zodiac is determined by your birth year. It influences personality analysis, marriage compatibility, career choices, and even baby planning — Dragon years consistently see birth rate spikes across Chinese communities worldwide. Understanding the zodiac is essential for anyone interested in Chinese culture.</p>

<h2 id="origin">Origin of the Chinese Zodiac</h2>

  <p>The most famous origin story is the Great Race. The Jade Emperor (玉皇大帝) invited all animals to a race across a river — the first 12 to cross would earn a place in the zodiac.</p>

  <p>Historical records suggest that the Chinese zodiac system dates back over 2,000 years. The earliest known reference appears in Chinese texts from the Warring States period (475–221 BCE), though the system was likely practiced in folk tradition long before it was recorded in writing. Some scholars believe the zodiac may have originated from ancient Chinese astronomers who observed Jupiter's approximately 12-year orbit around the sun and divided the celestial path into 12 segments, each associated with an animal.</p>

  <p>Another theory ties the zodiac to early Chinese farming communities. Different animals held symbolic importance in agricultural life — the Ox represented hard labor in the fields, the Rooster signaled the start of a new day, and the Rat was associated with grain storage. Over centuries, these animal symbols became formalized into the 12-year cycle used for timekeeping and fortune-telling. By the Han Dynasty (206 BCE–220 CE), the zodiac system was widely established and had become an integral part of Chinese calendar culture, appearing on official documents and influencing court decisions.</p>

  <p>The Cat is notably absent from the zodiac. According to popular legend, the Rat tricked the Cat by promising to wake it up for the race but then leaving without it. This story is often used to explain why cats chase rats in real life. Interestingly, the Vietnamese zodiac replaces the Rabbit with the Cat, making it the only major zodiac variant where the Cat holds a position.</p>

