  <p>Each animal in the zodiac carries both positive and negative traits. For example, the Rat is considered resourceful and adaptable, but can also be seen as cunning or overly cautious. The Dragon is admired for its ambition and leadership ability, yet may be perceived as arrogant or domineering. The Pig, while generous and warm-hearted, is sometimes characterized as naive or indulgent. Understanding both sides of each animal's personality is important in Chinese culture — people often consider their zodiac weaknesses as areas for self-improvement rather than fixed character flaws.</p>

  <p>Career aptitudes are also associated with each animal. Rats are said to thrive in business and finance due to their sharp instincts. Tigers excel in leadership roles and competitive fields. Snakes are drawn to research, philosophy, and detective work because of their analytical minds. Horses prefer careers that offer freedom and variety, such as travel, journalism, or sales. These associations, while not taken as strict rules, often come up in casual career discussions and even in some traditional Chinese job-matching practices.</p>

  <h2 id="find-your-animal">Find Your Zodiac Animal</h2>

  <p>To find your zodiac animal, match your birth year to the 12-year cycle. But remember: the Chinese zodiac follows the <strong>lunar calendar</strong>, not January 1st. If you were born in January or early February, you may actually belong to the previous year's animal.</p>

  <div style="background: #fef3c7; border-radius: 8px; padding: 16px; margin: 16px 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0; font-weight: 600;">💡 Quick Formula:</p>
    <p style="margin: 8px 0 0;">The most common question in Chinese: <strong>你属什么？(nǐ shǔ shénme?)</strong> — What is your zodiac animal? Answer: <strong>我属[animal]。(wǒ shǔ...)</strong> — I am the [animal]. For example: 我属龙 (I am the Dragon).</p>
  </div>

  <p>The lunar calendar boundary is a common source of confusion. Chinese New Year falls on a different date each year, typically between January 21 and February 20. For example, someone born on February 1, 1990 might assume they are a Horse (1990 is a Horse year), but Chinese New Year in 1990 fell on January 27 — so anyone born before that date would actually be a Snake (the previous year's animal). Always check the exact date of Chinese New Year for your birth year before determining your zodiac sign.</p>

  <p>In modern China, asking someone's zodiac animal (你属什么？) is one of the most common icebreaker questions — similar to asking about star signs in Western countries. It is considered less direct than asking someone's age, yet it still reveals approximate age since the cycle repeats every 12 years. This makes it a culturally polite way to gauge someone's generation in social and professional settings.</p>

  <h2 id="compatibility">Zodiac Compatibility</h2>

  <p>Traditional Chinese astrology groups the 12 animals into four "trine" groups of three. Animals in the same trine are considered highly compatible:</p>

