  <p>Beyond the trine groups, there are also "secret friend" pairs — two animals with a special bond that brings mutual support. These pairs are: Rat and Ox, Tiger and Pig, Rabbit and Dog, Dragon and Rooster, Snake and Monkey, Horse and Goat. When secret friends appear together in a relationship or business partnership, they are believed to complement each other's strengths and cover each other's weaknesses. For instance, the detail-oriented Rooster helps the big-picture Dragon stay grounded, while the Dragon gives the Rooster confidence to aim higher.</p>

  <p>Zodiac compatibility plays a significant role in Chinese marriage traditions. Historically, families would consult a fortune teller (算命先生 suànmìng xiānshēng) to compare the zodiac signs and birth charts of a potential couple before approving an engagement. While this practice has become less rigid in modern urban China, many families — especially older generations — still consider zodiac compatibility when evaluating a prospective son-in-law or daughter-in-law. Some dating apps in China even include zodiac filters to match users with compatible signs.</p>

  <p>In business, zodiac compatibility influences partnership decisions and negotiation strategies in some traditional circles. A business owner born in a Rat year might prefer partnering with someone born under the Dragon or Monkey sign, as these trine allies are believed to share similar ambition and work styles. While younger professionals may dismiss this as superstition, awareness of zodiac dynamics remains a useful cultural skill when working with Chinese clients and colleagues.</p>

