  <p>The concept of Tai Sui deserves closer attention. In Chinese folk religion, Tai Sui is not a single deity but a group of 60 celestial generals, each governing one year of the full 60-year cycle (combining 12 animals with 5 elements). When your zodiac year returns, you are said to be "offending" (犯太岁 fàn tàisuì) the Tai Sui of that year. This is not limited to your exact zodiac animal — people whose signs clash with or harm the current year's animal are also considered to be in a Tai Sui conflict year, though the effect is believed to be milder.</p>

  <p>Beyond wearing red, many people take additional precautions during their Ben Ming Nian. Some visit a Tai Sui temple at the beginning of the lunar year to perform a ceremony called "paying respects to Tai Sui" (拜太岁 bài tàisuì), asking for the year god's protection. Others carry jade pendants engraved with their zodiac animal or a compatible animal as a protective talisman. In Taiwan and Hong Kong, it is also common to donate to charity during one's Ben Ming Nian, as performing good deeds is believed to offset potential bad luck.</p>

  <p>From a practical standpoint, many Chinese people use their Ben Ming Nian as a time for reflection and caution rather than bold action. Major life decisions such as changing careers, getting married, or making large investments are traditionally postponed if possible. Whether or not one believes in the superstition, the Ben Ming Nian serves as a cultural reminder to be thoughtful and deliberate — a concept that transcends belief in fortune-telling.</p>

