  <p>For Chinese language learners, zodiac-related vocabulary opens doors to deeper cultural conversations. Beyond the basic animal names listed above, here are useful phrases you will hear frequently: 属相合不合 (shǔxiàng hé bù hé) means "are the zodiac signs compatible?" — a question commonly asked about couples. 犯太岁 (fàn tàisuì) means "offending Tai Sui" and refers to being in a conflict year. 转运 (zhuǎn yùn) means "to change one's luck" and is often discussed during Ben Ming Nian. 八字 (bāzì) literally means "eight characters" and refers to the Four Pillars of Destiny used in detailed fortune-telling. Knowing these terms will help you understand conversations about zodiac culture that go beyond the basics.</p>

  <p>Zodiac vocabulary also appears in common Chinese idioms and expressions. 龙马精神 (lóng mǎ jīngshén) combines Dragon and Horse to mean "full of vigor and vitality." 鸡犬不宁 (jī quǎn bù níng) literally translates to "even the chickens and dogs are not at peace," meaning a household in chaos. 画蛇添足 (huà shé tiān zú) means "drawing a snake and adding feet" — doing something unnecessary that ruins the result. Learning these animal-based idioms is an excellent way to build both vocabulary and cultural literacy simultaneously.</p>

